Yes.

45:39.504 --> 45:42.306
Well, I've already been to Mexico a few times.

45:42.947 --> 45:44.208
I've been working on this book.

45:46.530 --> 45:59.802
It makes me sound like a maniac, but this is the fact of the matter, that this book had its gestation in 1988 when my wife and I went on a vacation on a whim.

45:59.822 --> 46:08.310
We went to the Yucatan, just on a whim, and I became intoxicated with the

46:08.746 --> 46:11.250
Mayan ruins in the Yucatan.

46:13.032 --> 46:18.741
And I said to her, you know, one day I want to come back and I want to do a book on this whole area of the world.

46:18.881 --> 46:20.143
I just, I have to.

46:20.183 --> 46:35.445
And, um, so this, then the next year we went back again on another vacation, and I first sort of took notes on the basic theme of the book.

46:35.678 --> 46:57.198
While all this other stuff was going on, A Man Ray was being finished and then Thomas Edison was being developed, this Mexico book was sort of slowly building up and I was acquiring books on that region and reading and doing a little research on it.

46:57.238 --> 46:58.939
Did you have a focus on the book, though, at that point?

47:00.120 --> 47:01.381
It's changed.

47:01.401 --> 47:05.365
At first it was going to be, as I called it, a fatal shore

47:06.290 --> 47:07.692
of the Yucatan.

47:09.474 --> 47:13.440
But that was too bombastic, too big.

47:14.421 --> 47:31.825
And then as I came to terms with the fact that I was a biographer, number one, I decided to focus on the major archetypal mythic figure of Mesoamerican culture.

47:32.564 --> 47:41.257
The Plumed Serpent, Quetzalcoatl is the Q-U-E-T-Z-A-L-C-O-A-T-L.

47:43.160 --> 48:00.968
And instead of writing a biography of a person's life, since another one of my interests has always been back in the poetry days, archetypes and cultural myths and beliefs and how they come to be,

48:01.842 --> 48:07.408
I decided to find out as much as I could about this figure.

48:07.649 --> 48:30.955
No one has ever taken the disparate stories from Aztec and Mayan cultures, the geographical iconography of the temples, the different versions of the story that have been passed down through the Spanish ethno-historians.

48:32.183 --> 48:49.767
No one has ever taken all of that and plugged them into the geographical progress of the myth from northeastern Mexico to the Yucatan, through time from 1500 BC to the present, and put them all together into a coherent story.

48:50.308 --> 48:53.452
How deeply are you into this, would you say?

48:53.472 --> 48:56.776
Well, I've read about 250 books.

48:56.897 --> 48:58.298
Has the writing started?

48:58.318 --> 48:58.519
No.

48:58.659 --> 49:00.942
I'm going to Mexico in April for two weeks.

49:01.377 --> 49:05.102
and it's due and the book is supposed to be handed in September of 96.

49:05.322 --> 49:13.812
I don't think it's going to be a problem because, as I say, it's sort of having this pre-writing process in my head.

49:14.914 --> 49:25.066
And, um, I have sort of had a running start in my research going back to the first time I went to Mexico.

49:28.010 --> 49:31.114
So, after that, I

49:31.634 --> 49:38.301
I can see myself going back to another sort of major biography, but I don't know what it's going to be about.

49:38.321 --> 49:42.646
Let's talk about Edison now, if we can.

49:42.666 --> 49:43.467
It's a good idea.

49:43.567 --> 49:46.069
Geographically.

49:46.229 --> 49:49.513
It's very important, and it'll all be useful.

49:49.613 --> 49:57.041
But now it's, what are we, 15 or 20 miles from, I mean, geographically?

49:57.822 --> 50:00.004
Five miles away.

50:00.642 --> 50:06.388
So let's talk a little bit about it.

50:06.668 --> 50:20.062
Was it the coincidence of proximity, or what was it that first sparked the interest in Edison, or was it this fascination for, you know, invention, genius?

50:21.003 --> 50:21.723
Two things.

50:22.104 --> 50:23.645
One, three things.

50:24.126 --> 50:30.092
The American story is a story that I've been concerned with for a long time,

50:30.376 --> 50:34.661
explain to you, the American cultural story, how it came to be.

50:35.061 --> 50:37.904
Going back to de Tocqueville, what does it mean?

50:37.944 --> 50:43.310
What is the American story, and who represents it, and who says it, who tells it?

50:43.330 --> 50:52.400
Number two, the nature of imagination and creativity is something that has preoccupied me for a long time.

50:53.160 --> 50:59.387
Number three, after Man Ray was finished, I went through this crisis of

51:00.262 --> 51:07.329
You know, this idealistic crisis that, well, any good biographer has to think of the subject himself.

51:08.270 --> 51:09.671
It's got to come from within.

51:09.691 --> 51:10.932
You know, you've got to think.

51:10.952 --> 51:12.233
So I couldn't think of anybody.

51:12.453 --> 51:22.603
So I started, you know, beating myself over the head, like, well, you know, if you can't think of anything, then I don't know what, you know, what worth are you.

51:22.643 --> 51:30.150
So I went out to lunch with James Atlas, the biographer of Delmar Schwartz, who's an editor of the New York Times.

51:30.502 --> 51:31.703
I told him this problem.

51:31.723 --> 51:34.786
He said, Neil, I didn't think of a Delmore Schwartz biography idea.

51:34.826 --> 51:35.767
That wasn't my idea.

51:35.807 --> 51:39.971
He said, Roger Strauss proposed that to me.

51:40.591 --> 51:42.913
And you don't have to think of it yourself.

51:42.993 --> 51:45.135
Don't get hung up on that, you know.

51:45.175 --> 51:55.665
And that was important by way of introducing the fact that this idea was proposed to me by Jenny Cox.

51:56.966 --> 51:57.927
We had lunch.

51:59.915 --> 52:05.240
She said, I want you to write a book for me, and I'm going to call you up every day and pitch you ideas.

52:05.260 --> 52:07.122
What a wonderful circumstance.

52:07.142 --> 52:11.006
Until we come up with a book for you to write for Hyperion.

52:12.888 --> 52:18.053
So her assistant starts calling me every few days.

52:18.233 --> 52:22.197
She must have had this terrific respect for your earlier work.

52:22.217 --> 52:22.638
Yeah.

52:24.700 --> 52:25.341
This is the guy.

52:26.141 --> 52:26.842
Thank God.

52:27.102 --> 52:29.685
I've been waiting for this.

52:31.032 --> 52:44.530
Jenny Cox, right again, Jenny Cox, uh, flowered the book, but she left, and Rick, do you know who Rick caught, uh, R-I-C-K, caught K-O-T?

52:45.191 --> 52:48.195
He is a, an incredible non-fiction editor.

52:48.215 --> 52:49.637
He, he was at HarperCollins.

52:50.899 --> 52:51.320
Ooh.

52:51.340 --> 52:52.321
There was a nice day.

52:54.123 --> 52:56.847
Coffee.

52:57.788 --> 52:58.329
Coffee?

52:58.349 --> 52:59.190
Is that you?

52:59.210 --> 52:59.270
No.

52:59.290 --> 53:00.432
Oh, you ought to, I'm sorry.

53:01.120 --> 53:07.389
Don't sleep at all.

53:07.830 --> 53:09.232
And the water.

53:09.733 --> 53:12.036
I drink a lot of water.

53:12.097 --> 53:16.023
All right.

53:16.704 --> 53:26.959
Rick was at HarperCollins for a long time, and he joined Hyperion in the fall of 90s.

53:28.019 --> 53:37.611
At which time my book was about two-thirds finished manuscript.

53:37.712 --> 53:42.278
Well, there were anxious moments when you switched editors like that.

53:42.738 --> 53:45.061
Well, there was a moment where I didn't have really anybody.

53:48.706 --> 53:57.317
But I knew that Rick was moving to Hyperion and he is probably one of the best non-fiction editors in the entire industry.

53:57.635 --> 53:58.936
He has a great reputation.

53:58.956 --> 53:59.937
He's highly respected.

54:01.258 --> 54:08.684
He did a gorgeous job on this manuscript.

54:08.704 --> 54:15.430
I'll tell you, I love the juxtaposition of the photos, the integration of the photos.

54:15.450 --> 54:16.691
I wanted to do it that way.

54:17.612 --> 54:19.213
Did you know it's cheaper to do it that way?

54:19.273 --> 54:20.114
No, I don't.

54:20.134 --> 54:22.696
We haven't even submitted the pictures in my book yet.

54:22.796 --> 54:25.919
I would love to have done it that way.

54:25.939 --> 54:27.540
It's just going to be a 16-page album.

54:28.060 --> 54:29.081
You know, so what.

54:29.101 --> 54:33.665
Well, I wanted, that goes back to my narrative idea.

54:33.725 --> 54:43.874
I wanted the pictures to tie in exactly to the text, and you'll probably see they really do hit exactly when I'm talking about whatever I'm talking about.

54:44.054 --> 54:46.877
But you have such wonderful pictures, too.

54:46.897 --> 54:49.319
Well, they're, that's, they really have a rocket.

54:49.359 --> 54:55.705
The photo research is done by me, and, um,

54:55.870 --> 54:59.220
Of course, I had a lot of experience with Man Ray doing all those photos.

55:02.770 --> 55:07.163
So what else can I tell you?

